## LECTURE 1.1 — THE SOC 2 FRAMEWORK: WHAT IT IS, WHY IT MATTERS, WHO CARES

1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:15,000
Looking at compliance frameworks can feel overwhelming.
So many standards, so much documentation, and the acronyms.

2
00:00:15,000 --> 00:00:30,000
It is enough to make anyone feel stuck.
But what if there was one framework that actually makes sense
for modern SaaS companies?

3
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:45,000
That is SOC 2.
Hi there, and welcome to a course where I will take you
from SOC 2 beginner to confident compliance lead.

4
00:00:45,000 --> 00:01:00,000
Without endless theory or aimless documentation reading.
This is about understanding what actually matters
while truly grasping why.

5
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:20,000
Starting from what SOC 2 is and why you should care,
to how each Trust Service Criterion applies to your actual infrastructure.
And finally building a complete evidence package
that would satisfy even the toughest auditor.

6
00:01:20,000 --> 00:01:40,000
By the end of this crash course, you will not just know SOC 2.
You will have created something you can showcase to customers and investors.

7
00:01:40,000 --> 00:02:00,000
But that is not all. For those ready to dive even deeper,
I have put together a comprehensive SOC 2 readiness guide.
Designed to take you from zero to audit-ready.

8
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:20,000
Whether it is learning evidence collection, remediation planning,
or working with auditors. You can find all the links in the description below.

9
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:40,000
But for now, let us dive into the video together.
We will build a complete compliance program using a real financial RAG agent
as our example system. Let us get started.

10
00:02:40,000 --> 00:03:00,000
SOC 2 is a game changer.
It is an auditing standard created by the AICPA.
The American Institute of Certified Public Accountants.

11
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:20,000
It has become the gold standard for SaaS companies worldwide.
Unlike ISO 27001 which is international,
SOC 2 is particularly popular in North America.

12
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:40,000
But global customers increasingly demand it.
And here is what makes it special.
It does not prescribe specific controls.

13
00:03:40,000 --> 00:04:00,000
Instead, it gives you five Trust Service Criteria.
And you get to choose which ones apply.
Let me break down the five TSCs.

14
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:20,000
First, Security.
This one is mandatory for everyone.
It means your system is protected against unauthorized access.

15
00:04:20,000 --> 00:04:40,000
Think API keys, database encryption, network policies.
All the foundational stuff.
Second, Availability.

16
00:04:40,000 --> 00:05:00,000
This is about your system being available for operation as agreed.
For most SaaS, that means uptime commitments.
Your ninety-nine point nine percent SLO, multi-AZ deployment.

17
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:20,000
All of that.
Third, Processing Integrity.
This means system processing is complete, accurate, and timely.

18
00:05:20,000 --> 00:05:40,000
For our financial RAG agent, this includes things like SHA-256 deduplication.
Ensuring we do not ingest the same SEC filing twice.
Fourth, Confidentiality.

19
00:05:40,000 --> 00:06:00,000
Information designated as confidential is protected.
In our system, that is SEC filing text before it is publicly filed.
Plus user queries.

20
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:20,000
Fifth, Privacy.
This covers personal information collected, used, retained, and disclosed.
If you collect emails or any PII, this applies.

21
00:06:20,000 --> 00:06:40,000
Now, there are two types of SOC 2 reports.
And this confuses everyone at first.
Type I evaluates whether your controls are designed appropriately
at a specific point in time.

22
00:06:40,000 --> 00:07:00,000
Think of it as an architecture review.
It takes about one to two months.
And costs twenty to fifty thousand dollars.

23
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:20,000
Type II evaluates whether those controls are operating effectively
over a period of time. Typically six to twelve months.
This is what customers really want.

24
00:07:20,000 --> 00:07:40,000
It proves you are not just designed well, but actually following through.
Type II takes four to eight months.
And costs fifty to one hundred fifty thousand dollars.

25
00:07:40,000 --> 00:08:00,000
The typical timeline looks like this.
Weeks one to two for scoping.
Weeks three to four for gap analysis.

26
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:20,000
Weeks five to eight for remediation.
Week nine for Type I fieldwork.
Week ten for delivery.

27
00:08:20,000 --> 00:08:40,000
Then you operate for six to twelve months collecting evidence.
Month thirteen for Type II fieldwork.
Month fourteen for final delivery.

28
00:08:40,000 --> 00:09:00,000
The key players in a SOC 2 audit are your auditor.
Typically the Big Four. Deloitte, PwC, KPMG, EY.
Or boutique firms.

29
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:20,000
The report recipients are your customers, investors,
and board of directors.
Your team includes security engineers, platform engineers,
and compliance leads.

30
00:09:20,000 --> 00:09:40,000
Let me show you how to map your system to these criteria
with a real example.
I am going to walk through mapping a financial RAG agent
to the five TSCs.

31
00:09:40,000 --> 00:10:00,000
Open your terminal and let us create our system boundary document.
Type mkdir dash p soc2.

32
00:10:00,000 --> 00:10:30,000
Now run cat greater than soc2/system-boundary.yaml with here document.
Let me write this out for you.

33
