## LECTURE 1.5 — TYPE I VS TYPE II: TIMELINES, COSTS, AND WHAT CUSTOMERS WANT

146
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:30,000
One of the first decisions you will make is whether to pursue
a Type I or Type II report.
And in what order.
Let me clear up the confusion.

147
00:00:30,000 --> 00:01:00,000
Type I evaluates design.
Are your controls designed appropriately to meet the trust criteria?
It is a point-in-time assessment.

148
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:30,000
Your auditor will look at your policies, your architecture diagrams,
your control implementations.
But they will not test whether they actually work over time.

149
00:01:30,000 --> 00:02:00,000
Type II evaluates operating effectiveness.
Not only are your controls designed well,
but they have been working properly over a period of time.
Typically six to twelve months.

150
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:30,000
Here is the comparison table that matters.
Type I proves controls are designed appropriately.
Duration is point-in-time.
Evidence needed includes design documents and configurations.

151
00:02:30,000 --> 00:03:00,000
Timeline is one to two months.
Cost is twenty to fifty thousand dollars.
Customer value shows intent.

152
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:30,000
Type II proves controls are operating effectively.
Duration is six to twelve months.
Evidence needed includes operational logs and monitoring data.

153
00:03:30,000 --> 00:04:00,000
Timeline is four to eight months.
Cost is fifty to one hundred fifty thousand dollars.
Customer value shows proven operation.

154
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:30,000
Most companies do Type I first, then Type II about six to twelve months later.
Here is why.
Type I gives you something to show customers
while you are building the operational history for Type II.

155
00:04:30,000 --> 00:05:00,000
Here is the typical timeline I recommend.
Months one to two. Scoping and readiness assessment.
Months three to four. Control gap analysis.

156
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:30,000
Months five to eight. Remediation. Building missing controls.
Month nine. Type I audit fieldwork.
Month ten. Type I report delivery.

157
00:05:30,000 --> 00:06:00,000
Months ten to sixteen. Continuous operation and evidence collection.
Month seventeen. Type II audit fieldwork.
Month eighteen. Type II report delivery.

158
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:30,000
Now let me show you how to assess your readiness.
Create scripts forward slash readiness-check dot sh.

159
00:06:30,000 --> 00:07:00,000
Start with echo SOC 2 Readiness Check.
For CC6.1, check API key authentication.
Look for API_KEY_ENABLED in the deployment environment variables.

160
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:30,000
For CC6.6, check RDS encryption.
Verify StorageEncrypted is true.
For CC6.7, check TLS for ALB.
Look for TLS configuration in the ingress.

161
00:07:30,000 --> 00:08:00,000
For CC7.1, check Prometheus metrics.
Look for a ServiceMonitor.
For CC7.4, check Velero backups.
Look for a completed backup.

162
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:30,000
For CC8.1, check GitHub branch protection.
Verify required pull request reviews are configured.
Each check outputs a green check mark if present,
a red X if missing.

163
00:08:30,000 --> 00:09:00,000
Here is what customers actually care about.
When a customer asks for your SOC 2 report,
enterprise customers want Type II with all five trust criteria.

164
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:30,000
Mid-market customers often accept Type I initially,
but want Type II within a year.
Startup customers might only care about Security.

165
00:09:30,000 --> 00:10:00,000
Pro tip. Do not wait for perfection.
Get a Type I report as soon as your basic controls are in place.
It is much easier to sell with a Type I report than with nothing.

166
00:10:00,000 --> 00:10:30,000
Your lab exercise is to run the readiness check script
against your environment.
For each missing control, create a remediation ticket.

167
00:10:30,000 --> 00:11:00,000
Estimate how long each fix will take.
That becomes your roadmap to Type I.
Once you have completed that, move on to Lecture one point six.

168
00:11:00,000 --> 00:11:30,000
Where we will walk through an auditor interview.

