## LECTURE 1.6 — THE AUDITOR WALKTHROUGH: FIVE QUESTIONS AND HOW TO ANSWER THEM

169
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:30,000
The auditor walkthrough is where SOC 2 readiness lives or dies.
This is when the auditor meets with your team
to understand your system and controls.

170
00:00:30,000 --> 00:01:00,000
They are not trying to fail you.
They are trying to understand.
But if you cannot explain your controls clearly,
they will note gaps.

171
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:30,000
Let me walk you through the five most common questions
and exactly how to answer them.

172
00:01:30,000 --> 00:02:00,000
Question one. How do you ensure only authorized users access the system?
Here is your answer template.

173
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:30,000
Our system implements defense-in-depth for access control.
At the edge, all API requests require a valid API key
with rotation every ninety days.

174
00:02:30,000 --> 00:03:00,000
Internally, Kubernetes RBAC restricts what service accounts can do.
For database access, Vault provides dynamic credentials
with a one hour TTL.

175
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:30,000
Network policies enforce zero-trust between services.
And all access attempts are logged with a unique request ID for audit.

176
00:03:30,000 --> 00:04:00,000
Now show them the evidence.
Run grep with A10 on APIKeyMiddleware in the middleware file.
Run kubectl get roles and rolebindings to show RBAC configuration.

177
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:30,000
Run vault read database forward slash creds forward slash rag-app
to show dynamic credentials.
Run kubectl logs on the API deployment filtered for API key
to show audit logs.

178
00:04:30,000 --> 00:05:00,000
Question two. How do you detect and respond to security incidents?
Answer template.

179
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:30,000
We use Falco for runtime security with eBPF probes
monitoring system calls.
We have written custom rules for RAG-specific threats.

180
00:05:30,000 --> 00:06:00,000
Like unauthorized EDGAR or OpenAI access.
Alerts route to PagerDuty with severity-based escalation.
Incident response runbooks are version-controlled in Git.

181
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:30,000
And we conduct post-incident reviews with evidence collection
for every security event.

182
00:06:30,000 --> 00:07:00,000
Evidence to show. Cat the Falco rules file.
Kubectl get configmap for falcosidekick to show PagerDuty integration.
Ls runbooks to show they exist.

183
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:30,000
And kubectl logs on the Falco daemonset filtered for alerts.

184
00:07:30,000 --> 00:08:00,000
Question three. How do you ensure data integrity
and prevent unauthorized changes?
Answer template.

185
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:30,000
Data integrity starts at ingestion.
SHA-256 deduplication ensures we never process the same SEC filing twice.
For changes, we use GitOps with ArgoCD.

186
00:08:30,000 --> 00:09:00,000
Which prevents manual kubectl changes.
All code changes require PR reviews with at least one approver.
Database changes are audited in the analysis_history table.

187
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:30,000
And we maintain point-in-time recovery capable backups.

188
00:09:30,000 --> 00:10:00,000
Evidence. Grep for file_hash in the SEC ingestor.
Argocd app get to show sync status.
And psql to count records in analysis_history for the last thirty days.

189
00:10:00,000 --> 00:10:30,000
Question four. How do you ensure system availability meets SLAs?
Answer template.

190
00:10:30,000 --> 00:11:00,000
We target ninety-nine point nine percent availability
with multi-AZ deployment for both RDS and EKS.
The API automatically scales from three to twenty replicas
based on CPU utilization using HPA.

191
00:11:00,000 --> 00:11:30,000
Karpenter provisions new nodes in under thirty seconds
during scale-up events.
PodDisruptionBudgets ensure minimum two replicas during maintenance.

192
00:11:30,000 --> 00:12:00,000
Our SLO dashboard in Grafana tracks rolling thirty-day availability.

193
00:12:00,000 --> 00:12:30,000
Question five. How do you manage third-party vendor risks?
Answer template.

194
00:12:30,000 --> 00:13:00,000
We maintain a vendor register for all third parties
that process customer data.
For high-risk vendors like OpenAI, we have reviewed their SOC 2 Type II report
and executed a data processing agreement.

195
00:13:00,000 --> 00:13:30,000
AWS is covered under the shared responsibility model.
Their physical and environmental controls are inherited.
All vendors are reassessed annually.

196
00:13:30,000 --> 00:14:00,000
Here is the vendor register you should maintain in vendor-register dot yaml.
OpenAI has service LLM API, risk level high,
assessment date 2026-01-15.

197
00:14:00,000 --> 00:14:30,000
Controls include SOC 2 Type II report reviewed,
data processing agreement executed,
and subprocessor list reviewed.
Next review 2026-07-15.

198
00:14:30,000 --> 00:15:00,000
AWS has service cloud infrastructure, risk level medium.
Controls include Shared Responsibility Model documented
and AWS SOC 2 report reviewed.

199
00:15:00,000 --> 00:15:30,000
Next review 2026-07-15.
SEC EDGAR has service public data source, risk level low.
Controls include public data only and no customer data shared.

200
00:15:30,000 --> 00:16:00,000
Next review 2027-01-15.

201
00:16:00,000 --> 00:16:30,000
Your lab exercise is to conduct a mock auditor interview with your team.
Have one person play the auditor, asking these five questions.
Practice until you can answer smoothly without looking at notes.

202
00:16:30,000 --> 00:17:00,000
Record the session and review what could be clearer.
Once you have completed that, move on to Lecture one point seven.
Where we will create a remediation plan for any gaps.

